Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}. Chop the tops and bottoms off the @courgette{1} and quarter each courgette lengthways. Cut each strip into 1cm chunks.

Dissolve the @vegetable stock pot{1} in 350ml of boiling water and keep to one side.

Heat a #saucepan{} over medium heat and add @oil{1%tbsp}. Stir in the garlic and add the @Sri Lankan spice blend{2%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute} and then add the @basmati rice{1/2%cup} to the pan. Mix well to make sure the spices are evenly distributed. Add the courgette and pour in the stock. Bring to the boil and then pop a #lid{} on. Reduce the heat to low and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

After ~{10%minutes} remove the pan from the heat and stir in the @king prawns{150%g}. Leave the pan off the heat with the lid on for another ~{10%minutes}, to allow the heat of the rice to cook the prawns and the rice to finish cooking.

As the rice and prawns get acquainted, finish off your last few jobs! Zest the @lemon{1/2}(zested) into a #bowl{} and roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}(roughly chopped). Mix half of the parsley with the lemon zest and add @olive oil{1 1/2%tbsp}.

Peel the @beetroot{1} and remove the top and bottom. Grate the beetroot on the coarse side of your #grater{} and mix in a bowl with the lemon zest and parsley. Squeeze in the juice of half a lemon.

Check your prawns are cooked. They should be pink on the outside and white all the way through. Squeeze in the juice of the other half of the lemon, the remaining parsley and mix well.

Serve a generous amount of your pilaf (share your prawns out evenly!) and top with some of your zesty slaw.

> Sri Lanka - they call it the pearl of India - because it really is that beautiful. The food is one of its main treasures and as an island - just like us - they love a dish with some tasty, fresh seafood. Plus, we've added gorgeous, wonderful beetroot, because it's in season so therefore at its most delicious! Fusion!